I noticed that typically the error log also includes `ec` (see line 31 above). It should probably be included here too

See https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/60384/10/COMMON_ERRORS.md 
I think this is okay, but this is right on the edge of a long lambda callback
Sometimes we have a default of Enabled but we aren't consistent so I think this is fine

CableCollection, the name of the schema

https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/v1/CableCollection.json
For general convention, do we expect cables to be enabled by default? Shouldn't it be other way round where we assume cables to be absent and only mark them enabled once they are inserted/present?

Here are 2 examples of the default to Enabled when the interface isn't there 
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/59739/2/redfish-core/lib/storage.hpp

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/processor.hpp#L101

Yeah the logic is same, I was talking about convention in general not particular to the code logic. May be it's just me to which it makes more sense to have status disabled and enabling it after hw detection or some other parametrics.
It should not return internalError if ec.value == EBADR right?
For this particular case, would it be resourceNotFound error?
It has the if check above for the interface so error if you don't have it. If you don't have it, internalError. I think what you had before was fine. I guess this is also fine.
Nit: please remove the blank line above.

Code looks good to me.
CI failures are fixed in https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/61426
